  "transcripts": [
    {
      "id": "int_2025_04_15",
      "date": "2025-04-15",
      "duration_min": 34,
      "sme_id": "sme_mike_karolczak",
      "interviewer": "Interviewer Agent",
      "topic": "Panel-cause fires, 4A, prior loss history",
      "excerpt": "MIKE: The tell for me is always three things stacked. Endorsement 4A, prior loss on the policy, and something in the first-notice that reads like a panel cause. When you see all three, you slow down. You don't lowball the reserve, but you don't blow it out either — you set it modestly, hold ALE conservative for the first ten days, and you wait for origin. Nine times out of ten it comes back panel, and nine times out of ten by then you've already got a subro angle because there's a recall list a mile long on these things.\n\nINTERVIEWER: How do you know it's panel-cause from the first notice?\n\nMIKE: The language. \"Popping sound before the smoke,\" \"lights flickered,\" fire concentrated at the electrical service entrance. Sometimes the fire department has already flagged it. You develop an ear for it.\n\nINTERVIEWER: And the ROR — when do you decide to reserve rights?\n\nMIKE: Prior loss plus 4A plus a panel signature — I reserve rights every time. Not because I think it's fraud — usually it isn't. Because 4A dwelling extension opens the exposure so wide I need the option to reduce if origin comes back somewhere I didn't expect. If it's clean panel, we release the ROR and pay clean. Insured understands. I always call and tell them what an ROR is before they get the letter.\n\nINTERVIEWER: What do you tell them?\n\nMIKE: I tell them the truth. I say — this is a big claim, our engineer has to look at the panel, and while he does we're keeping our options open, but I have zero reason to think anything is wrong. Then when the report comes back clean I call them back the same day and tell them we're paying. That's how you keep a customer for life.\n\nINTERVIEWER: And subrogation?\n\nMIKE: The panel manufacturers have been on notice for a decade. If the origin report calls out a specific model, we file. It's not fast money but it moves the loss ratio."
    },
    {
      "id": "int_2025_04_22",
      "date": "2025-04-22",
      "duration_min": 28,
      "sme_id": "sme_mike_karolczak",
      "interviewer": "Interviewer Agent",
      "topic": "Reserve setting, ALE, edge cases",
      "excerpt": "MIKE: You reserve for what you know, not what you fear. That's the discipline. Everybody wants to over-reserve to feel safe. It hurts the book and it hurts the insured because ALE decisions get slow. My rule — set to the median outcome for the pattern you're seeing, mark for review at day ten and day thirty, and let origin change the number, not your imagination.\n\nINTERVIEWER: You mentioned holding ALE conservative early. Why?\n\nMIKE: Because ALE is where sympathy inflates costs. If you commit to a six-week hotel on day two and origin comes back arson-suspicious on day nine, you're stuck. Hold two weeks, be honest with the insured that you'll extend the moment origin clears, and communicate. The insured almost always respects that.\n\nINTERVIEWER: What's the pattern you miss most often when training juniors?\n\nMIKE: Panel-cause without a 4A. Junior adjusters see no endorsement, they treat it like a garden fire. But panel-cause without 4A can still trigger the manufacturer recall subro, and if you don't preserve the evidence you burn the subro. Preserve the panel. Always. Even in the small fires."
    }
  ],
